  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This research, titled \"Permanent deconstruction of intracellular primary cilia in differentiating granule cell neurons,\" has made significant academic strides with 26 citations since its posting on bioRxiv in 2023. The work has not only influenced the academic landscape, particularly within the field of cellular biology, but has also been formally published in a peer-reviewed venue, reflecting its traversal through the scrutiny of scientific review.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The study exploring the dynamics of primary cilia in granule cell neurons demonstrates substantial academic engagement with a total of 26 citations shortly after its initial preprint on bioRxiv. This early sharing exemplifies a commitment to open science, with the researchers facilitating immediate community engagement and contributing to faster knowledge dissemination within the field. The subsequent formal publication further showcases the work\u2019s scientific rigor, as it has successfully navigated the peer review process to be included in a recognized journal.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The key institutions involved, including the Howard Hughes Medical Institute and Harvard University, underline the research's robust academic backing, which bolsters its credibility and reach in the scientific community. Additionally, the work has proven its influence beyond borders, with citations emerging from diverse geographical areas such as the United States and Turkey, suggesting a broad international interest in the findings.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Importantly, the research has shown effective downstream reuse, as evidenced by a count of 27 proven instances where materials or data from the study have actively enabled further research. This highlights the foundational nature of the findings and their potential impact on ongoing and future investigations in similar areas. Such reuse not only reflects the utility of the work but also emphasizes its relevance in advancing scientific knowledge.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In this rapidly evolving field, the contributions of this research are significant, shining a light on the mechanisms through which neuronal differentiation occurs. By addressing the role of primary cilia in granule cell neurons, the authors pave the way for deeper understanding and potential applications in neurobiology. The cumulative impact of both the preprint and the published version signifies that this work is not only noteworthy in its immediate contributions but is set to shape future explorations in the field of cellular signaling.</p>",
